AGI - In the south of the United States the Carmelite nuns of the Most Holy Trinity monastery in Arlington, Texas, initiated a lawsuit in court, challenging the Vatican that had decided the closure of the monastery after the superior mother broke the vow of chastity with video chat clashes with a priest. The case ended in court in an unprecedented legal dispute. The nuns asked to block the measure initiated by Bishop Michael Olson and denounced him, the diocese of Fort Worth and the Association of Christ the King in the United States, a private Catholic organization.&nbsp;
The initiative started after the decree issued last week by the Vatican that assigned the ecclesiastical association full control over the nuns and the monastery. Everything was born after the accusations launched to the superior mother, Teresa Agnes Gerlach, of having broken the vow of chastity with phone calls from sexual content with the priest of another monastery. Gerlach, who has always rejected the charges, was sent away last year at the end of an internal investigation conducted by the Vatican and led by Bishop Olson. In recent days the monastery, in an official statement, spoke of "continuous attacks and abuses" by the bishop in a "horrent attempt to take control of our administration and our lives and finances". &nbsp;
"We pray - they added as a challenge - that the Bishop of Fort Worth repents and asks publicly and to us in person. Until this happens, neither he nor his delegates will be welcome in our property."
In the case the nuns also ask 100 thousand dollars of compensation. A representative of the diocese responded, claiming that the Carmelite nuns, in the complaint, say they want to "respond directly only to the Pope", which the diocese does not consider legitimate. "We're going to try to get the expost stored in the appropriate time," he concluded, showing optimism. But the nuns have already announced that they are ready to all to maintain control of the monastery.
At their side the family of the heirs of the man who had donated years ago the land for the construction of the monastery. It is a large area about thirty hectares worth at least five million dollars. The diocese is convinced that it can be sold for a figure of four times greater. And that's exactly what was suspicious of the nuns, who fear to be victims of a bigger plan started with accusations to the superior mother.

