AGI -&nbsp; The UN is not involved in the negotiations between Egypt and Israel on the ceasefire, but hopes that the "necks are fruitful and that we will see the ceasefire humanitarian". The spokesman Stephane Dujarric said this, commenting on the news about the journey of another Egyptian delegation to Israel. The time strings: either there is an agreement on the truce, without Hamas having further obstacles, or the military operation on Rafah by the Israeli armed forces will be scattered. A condition, the latter, that the international community is trying to prevent, beginning with the same UN, convinced that&nbsp; the hygienic-sanitary crisis in Rafah, in the south of the Gaza Strip, is destined to aggravate itself with the increase of the expected temperature in the coming weeks. Today there were 40 degrees. "And we are only at the end of April - added Dujarric -. Our humanitarian colleagues remind us that more than a million people, between men, women and children, are sheltered in the area."&nbsp;
&nbsp;
An Egyptian source, according to &nbsp; reports the Jerusalem Post, says that "there are no talks about the hostages between Israel and Hamas, there is no new Israeli offer about it." "There is an attempt by Egypt to restart talks with an Egyptian proposal that would lead to the release of 33 hostages: women, elderly and sick." The Israeli newspaper, citing an official informed about the meetings, reports that an Egyptian delegation met with Israeli officials, looking for a way to restart talks to end the war in Gaza and return the remaining Israeli hostages. The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that Israel has no new proposals to make, although he is prepared to take into account a limited truce in which 33 hostages would be released, instead of the 40 previously discussed.
&nbsp;
Israeli intelligence officials believe that there are 33 women, elders, and hostage-going sick in Gaza, on a total of 133 still held by Hamas and other Palestinian terrorist groups. No decision was taken on the duration of the truce, but if such an exchange was agreed, the break in the fights would be "seriously less than six weeks", the official said. The visit of the Egyptian delegation followed the news of the Israeli media of a visit to Cairo on Thursday of the Israeli army leader, Lieutenant General Herzi Halevi, and Ronen Bar, the head of Shin Bet, Israeli intelligence service. Egypt, concerned about potential influx of Palestinian refugees from nearby Gaza if the war continues with the long-promised Israeli offensive in the southern city of &nbsp; Rafah, has played an increasingly active role in the negotiations.
&nbsp;
UN spokesman Stephane Dujarric, speaking of the nineteen members of the UN agency for Palestinian refugees accused by Israel of being linked to the Hamas militia, explained that they remain under investigation in fourteen, while in one case no evidence was found, and four others remain "suspended" waiting for new evidence. Suspects are divided into two groups: the first, made up of 12 people, concerns accusations launched in January by Israel, who had spoken of "clear trials" of the mix between members of the Unrwa and Hamas. The second, formed by nine, concerns allegations reported in March and April. Of the first group of 12, eight remain under investigation, while one was filed. The remaining three remain suspended because "the information provided so far by Israel is not enough to start an investigation." About the second group of seven, one is suspended waiting for new evidence. The other six remain under investigation. The UN inspectors added the spokesman, went to Israel to discuss with the authorities and planned a new trip to May.&nbsp;

